				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\tau $$\end{document}τ leptons) and the other decays hadronically. Events in which both top quarks decay semileptonically define the dilepton background, and are thus removed from the signal simulation.

The algorithm starts with the reconstruction of the neutrino four-momentum. The z-component of the neutrino momentum is calculated using the W boson mass constraint imposed on the invariant mass of the system of the charged lepton and the neutrino. If the resulting quadratic equation has two real solutions, the one with smallest absolute value of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$|p_z|$$\end{document}|pz| is chosen. If the determinant is negative, only the real part is considered. The leptonic W boson is reconstructed from the charged lepton and the neutrino and the leptonic top quark is reconstructed from the leptonic W and the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$b\text{-tagged }$$\end{document}b-tagged jet closest in \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta R$$\end{document}ΔR to the charged lepton. The hadronic W boson is reconstructed from the two non-b-tagged jets whose invariant mass is closest to the mass of the W boson. This choice yields the best performance of the algorithm in terms of the correlation between detector, particle and parton levels. Finally, the hadronic top quark is reconstructed from the hadronic W boson and the other \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$b\text{-jet }$$\end{document}b-jet. In events with more than two b-tagged jets, only the two with the highest transverse momentum are considered.

The shape of the distributions of the kinematical variables of this background is evaluated with a Monte Carlo simulation, and the event yields are normalized to the most recent calculations of their cross-sections, as described in Sect. 3. The overlap between the Wt and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${t\bar{t}}$$\end{document}tt¯ samples is handled using the diagram removal scheme [54].

The corrections for generator mis-modelling in the fractions of W boson production associated with jets of different flavour components (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
